,"Carries no risks to the embryo","Provides low-cost screening","Has low false negative rates"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPreimplantation genetic diagnosis (PGD) allows genetic testing of embryos before implantation, which is its main advantage. \u003Cstrong\u003ETesting before implantation\u003C/strong\u003E means that only embryos without the genetic condition of concern are selected for transfer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPGD has relatively \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigh false positive rates\u003C/strong\u003E due to embryonic mosaicism, where different cells in the same embryo can have different genetic compositions. The procedure carries \u003Cstrong\u003Erisks to the embryo\u003C/strong\u003E as it requires cell biopsy. It is an \u003Cstrong\u003Eexpensive screening\u003C/strong\u003E method as it must be combined with in vitro fertilisation. \u003Cstrong\u003EFalse negative rates\u003C/strong\u003E can also be significant due to technical limitations of testing single cells and mosaicism.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Preimplantation genetic diagnosis allows detection of specific genetic conditions before embryo implantation at a significant cost","False positive and false negative rates in preimplantation genetic diagnosis are relatively high due to technical limitations and mosaicism"],"references":["Fragouli E. Preimplantation genetic diagnosis: present and future. J Assist Reprod Genet. 2007 Jun;24(6):201-7. doi: 10.1007/s10815-007-9112-2. PMID: 17333365; PMCID: PMC3454965.","Sueoka K. Preimplantation genetic diagnosis: an update on current technologies and ethical considerations. Reprod Med Biol. 2015 Nov 14;15(2):69-75. doi: 10.1007/s12522-015-0224-6. PMID: 29259423; PMCID: PMC5715849."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57071"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15755"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}